<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=5081&amp;p=8163#p8163"><![CDATA[
To keep this thread alive, I will add my correspondence with whatwg.<br /><br />Willabee<br /><br /><br />    &gt; Please see <!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?f=3&amp;t=5081">viewtopic.php?f=3&amp;t=5081</a><!-- l --> for<br />    &gt; the background of my request to have &lt;acronym&gt; added to the HTML5<br />    &gt; spec.<br />    &gt;<br />    &gt;<br />    &gt;<br />    &gt; *Summary*<br />    &gt;<br />    &gt; Without getting into all of the discussions about what is an<br />    &gt; abbreviation and what is an acronym, I would like to propose the<br />    &gt; &lt;acronym&gt; element be added to the semantics of HTML5 with a clear<br />    &gt; indication of its semantic use;<br />    &gt;<br />    &gt; […]<br /><br />    I just found &lt;http://camendesign.com/code/using-abbr&gt; where it is<br />    suggested to use an abbr element without a title attribute to indicate<br />    that the abbreviation “is unpronouncable as a word”.<br /><br />    &lt;http://camendesign.com/abbr_redux&gt; backtracks: “Do not use [abbr] on<br />    initialisms that are spoken letter-by-letter”, “Only use abbr without a<br />    title on initialisms that should be pronounced as written rather than<br />    read out letter-by-letter”.<br /><br />    Is this acceptable?<br /><br />    --<br />    Nils Dagsson Moskopp // erlehmann<br />    &lt;http://dieweltistgarnichtso.net&gt;<br /><br />Nils,<br /><br />No.<br /><br />The second reference, which is an update to the first reference, makes very good reading and a lot of sense. I could go with this but ...<br /><br />It is not the spec. for HTML5. It is one man's view of trying to make &lt;abbr&gt; work. Other people/devices will interpret-ate &lt;abbr&gt; differently and have their own views of how to best implement the element.<br /><br />Here is a statement from the reference:<br /><br />'Because HTML5 removed &lt;acronym&gt; this is the only instance you should use abbr without a title to indicate to users and screen readers that the initialism should be pronounced rather than spelt out.'.<br /><br />What if the &lt;acronym&gt; needs a title? This special rule, an &lt;abbr&gt; without a title (assuming everyone learns it), has lost its meaning and will not be said as a word.<br /><br />I buy it that many abbreviations do not need to be marked up because they are obvious and people can find out what the meaning is elsewhere. I also can see great value in using the title to fit in with the flow of the spoken content but ...<br /><br />Everyone would learn very quickly that an &lt;acronym&gt; is used when we want the abbreviation to be spoken as a word.<br /><br />This would even fit in with the advice given in Kroc's article and he could drop the special meaning &lt;abbr&gt; without a title example.<br /><br />Now Kroc would just use &lt;acronym&gt; by itself to fit in with his example. Every person/device would know to speak the word. Kroc would be happy and all his other advise would stand. Others could now use the title attribute with &lt;acronym&gt; if they so desire. The word would still be spoken and not spelt out letter by letter. We now have the correct semantic element to do the right thing. Everybody is happy. Especially me.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3652">Willabee</a> — Mon Oct 15, 2012 7:42 pm</p><hr />
